Exercici 57

An investor wants to compare the risks associated to two different stocks, A and B. Market risk is measured using the variance of the daily changes in stock prices. The investor believes that the risk in market A is lower than the risk in market B. Two random samples are selected, consisting of 21 observations on the changes of prices in market A and 16 observations on the changes of prices in market B. The results are:

Market A Market B
\(X_A = 0.3\) \(X_B = 0.3\)
\(S_A = 0.45\) \(S_B = 0.25\)

Assuming that both samples come from two Normal and independent populations, does the data support the investor‚Äôs belief ? (Œ± = 0.05)

Definim les hip√≤tesis primer. Com que el risc es mesura utilitzant la vari√†ncia, el que volem veure √©s si la vari√†ncia del stock del Market A √©s m√©s petita que la vari√†ncia del stock del Market B:

\(H_0: \ \sigma^2_A \ge \sigma^2_B\)
\(H_1: \ \sigma^2_A < \sigma^2_B\)

L‚Äôestad√≠stic de la prova (observed value of test statistic, OVTS) √©s \(S_A^2 / S_B^2\).

sa <- 0.45
sb <- 0.25
(OVTS <- sa^2 / sb^2)  # 3.24
## [1] 3.24

Ara busquem l‚Äôestad√≠stic de contrast, el qual es basa en la distribuci√≥ \(F_{na -1, nb -1}\). Al tractar-se d‚Äôun test unilateral esquerra (\(H_1: \sigma^2_A < \sigma^2_B\)) i que la significaci√≥ √©s \(\alpha = 0.05\), l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig ser√†:

\([0, F_{na -1, nb -1, alpha}]\)

na <- 21
nb <- 16
alpha <- 0.05
(qf( p = alpha, df1 = na-1, df2 = nb-1 ))  # 0.45387 
## [1] 0.45387

L‚ÄôOVTS es troba fora de la regi√≥ de rebuig ja que \(3.24 \notin [0, 0.46]\). Per tant, donada la mostra, no podem rebutjar la hip√≤tesi alternativa. No podem dir que hi ha menys risc al Market A que al Market B.

Gr√†ficament:

L‚Äô√†rea en verd ens mostra a l‚Äôeix de les x la regi√≥ de no rebuig de la \(H_0\), entre 0.45 i +Inf, mentres que l‚Äô√†rea en vermell ens mostra l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig de \(H_0\), entre 0 i 0.45 Com que el nostre estad√≠stic (3.24) queda dintre de la regi√≥ d‚Äôacceptaci√≥, (l√≠nia negra) no rebutgem \(H_0\)

Exercici 59

In a Hospital 7 patients were selected, observing that they slept 7, 5, 8, 8.5, 6, 7 i 8 hours respectively. All of them were given a new sleeping pill, and then 5 of them were selected, observing 9, 8.5, 9.5, 10 i 8 sleep hours respectively. Is the new pill effective ? (Assume normality and \(\alpha\) = 0.05)

Volem veure si el medicament augmenta les hores de son dels pacients. Aix√≠ doncs, les hip√≤tesis les definim com:

\(H_0: \ \mu_1 - \mu_2 \ge 0\)
\(H_1: \ \mu_1 - \mu_2 < 0\)

Ara b√©, s‚Äôha de comprovar si les vari√†ncies s√≥n iguals, pel que definim tamb√©:

\(H_0: \ \sigma^2_1 = \sigma^2_2\)
\(H_1: \ \sigma^2_1 \ne \sigma^2_2\)

no_pill <- c(7, 5, 8, 8.5, 6, 7, 8)
si_pill <- c(9, 8.5, 9.5, 10, 8)
( s21 <- var( no_pill) ) # 1.535714
( s22 <- var( si_pill) ) # 0.625
( OVTS <- s21 / s22 )    # 2.457143
## [1] 1.535714
## [1] 0.625
## [1] 2.457143

Ara busquem l‚Äôestad√≠stic de contrast, el qual es basa en la distribuci√≥ \(F_{na -1, nb -1}\). Al tractar-se d‚Äôun test bilateral (\(H_1: \sigma^2_A \ne \sigma^2_B\)) i que la significaci√≥ √©s \(\alpha = 0.05\), l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig ser√†:

\([0, F_{na -1, nb -1, alpha/2}]\) i \([F_{na -1, nb -1, 1 - alpha/2}, +\infty]\)

n1 <- length( no_pill ) # 7
n2 <- length( si_pill ) # 5
alpha <- 0.05
FVTS1 <- qf(alpha/2, df1 = n1-1, df2 = n2-1 )  # 0.1605868
FVTS2 <- qf(1-alpha/2, df1 = n1-1, df2 = n2-1 ) # 9.197311

Com que 2.45 no est√† dintre de l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig \([0,0.16]\cup[9.19,+\infty]\), no rebutgem \(H_0\), √©s a dir, no podem dir que les vari√†ncies siguin diferents.

Gr√†ficament:

Ara, utilitzant el resutlat anterior, podem dir que l‚Äôestad√≠stic de la prova √©s:

\(\frac{\bar{X_1} - \bar{X_2}}{\sqrt{\frac{S^2}{n_1} + \frac{S^2}{n2} }} \quad\) on \(\quad S^2 = \frac{(n_1 -1)S^2_1 + (n_2 -1)S^2_2}{n_1 + n_2 -2}\)

El qual, sota la hip√≤tesis nul.la, segueix una distribuci√≥ \(t_ {n_1+n_2-2}\). Al tractar-se d‚Äôun test unilateral i amb \(\alpha = 0.05\), la regi√≥ de rebuig es troba a l‚Äôesquerra delimitada pel valor cr√≠tic \(t_ {10, \alpha}\)

## [1] -1.812461

Per trobar l‚Äôestad√≠stic, cal calcular:

( m1 <- mean(no_pill) ) # 7.071429
( s21 <- var(no_pill) ) # 1.535714
( m2 <- mean(si_pill) ) # 9
( s22 <- var(si_pill) ) # 0.625
( S2 <- ( (n1 - 1) * s21 + ( n2 - 1 ) * s22) / ( n1 + n2 - 2 ) ) # 1.171429
## [1] 7.071429
## [1] 1.535714
## [1] 9
## [1] 0.625
## [1] 1.171429

\(\bar{X_1} = 7.07 \quad S^2_1 = 1.53\)
\(\bar{X_2} = 9 \quad S^2_2 = 0.62\)
\(S^2 = 1.17\)

Calculem l‚Äôestad√≠stic:

( OVTS <- (m1-m2) / sqrt( S2/n1 + S2/n2) ) # -3.043135
## [1] -3.043135

Donat qu el valor observat es troba fora la regi√≥ d‚Äôacceptaci√≥, -3.04 < -1.812, hi ha prou evid√®ncies per rebutjar \(H_0\).

Utilitzant l‚ÄôR, primer mirem si les vari√†ncies les podem considerar no diferents amb var.test() i despr√©s apliquem la funci√≥ t.test():

var.test(x=no_pill, y=si_pill, alternative = "two.sided", conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  no_pill and si_pill
## F = 2.4571, num df = 6, denom df = 4, p-value = 0.4035
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   0.2671588 15.3010246
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           2.457143

Com que el \(p\)-valor √©s m√©s gran que la significaci√≥, no podem dir que les vari√†ncies siguin diferents. Fem ara el t.test() tot indicant que les vari√†nces no s√≥n diferents (var.equal = TRUE):

t.test(x=no_pill, y=si_pill, alternative = "less", var.equal = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  no_pill and si_pill
## t = -3.0431, df = 10, p-value = 0.006198
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##        -Inf -0.7799334
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  7.071429  9.000000

Com que el \(p\)-valor\(=0.006\) √©s m√©s petit que \(\alpha = 0.05\), rebutgem \(H_0\). √âs a dir, no podem dir que el medicament no faci que els pacients dormin m√©s hores en mitjana.

Gr√†ficament:

Exercici 60

Random errors in two measuring tools follow Normal distributions \(N(0, \sigma^2_1)\) i \(N(0, \sigma^2_1)\). In a sample of size 7 the following measuring errors are observed:

First tool: 1.6, -0.9, -2.8, 3.1, 4.2, -1.0, 2.1
Second tool: 0.3, 0.7, -1.1, 2.0, 1.7, -0.8, -0.5

If we assume that the sampling was conducted over two normal and independent populations, can we conclude that the first tool is more precise than the second tool?

En aquest cas volem veure si la variabilitat de la primera eina √©s m√©s baixa que al de la segona eina. Aix√≠ doncs, les hip√≤tesis s√≥n:

\(H_0: \ \sigma^2_A \ge \sigma^2_B\)
\(H_1: \ \sigma^2_A < \sigma^2_B\)

L‚Äôestad√≠stic de la prova (OVTS) √©s \(S^2_A /S^2_B\), el calculem:

( s2a <- var( c(1.6, -0.9, -2.8, 3.1, 4.2, -1.0, 2.1) ) ) # 6.366667
( s2b <- var( c(0.3, 0.7, -1.1, 2.0, 1.7, -0.8, -0.5) ) ) # 1.469048
( OVTS <- s2a / s2b )  # 4.333874
## [1] 6.366667
## [1] 1.469048
## [1] 4.333874

Ara busquem l‚Äôestad√≠stic de contrast, el qual es basa en la distribuci√≥ \(F_{na -1, nb -1}\). Al tractar-se d‚Äôun test unilateral esquerra (\(H_1: \sigma^2_A < \sigma^2_B\)) i que la significaci√≥ √©s \(\alpha = 0.05\), l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig ser√†:

\([0, F_{na -1, nb -1, alpha}]\)

na <- length( c(1.6, -0.9, -2.8, 3.1, 4.2, -1.0, 2.1) ) # 7
nb <- length( c(0.3, 0.7, -1.1, 2.0, 1.7, -0.8, -0.5) ) # 7
alpha <- 0.05
(qf( p = alpha, df1 = na-1, df2 = nb-1 ))  # 0.233434
## [1] 0.233434

Com que l‚Äôestad√≠stic OVTS (4.33) es troba fora de regi√≥ de rebuig [0, 0.23], podem dir que donada la mostra hi ha prou evid√®ncia per a no rebutjar la hip√≤tesi nul.la. √âs a dir, no podem dir que la presici√≥ de la primera eina sigui m√©s alta que la de la segona eina.

En aquest cas al tenir les dues mostres, podem aplicar la funci√≥ var.test():

toolA <- c(1.6, -0.9, -2.8, 3.1, 4.2, -1.0, 2.1)
toolB <- c(0.3, 0.7, -1.1, 2.0, 1.7, -0.8, -0.5)
var.test(x=toolA, y=toolB, alternative = "less")
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  toolA and toolB
## F = 4.3339, num df = 6, denom df = 6, p-value = 0.9512
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is less than 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   0.00000 18.56573
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           4.333874

Pel que amb \(p\)-valor \(= 0.9512 > 0.05 = \alpha\), no rebutgem la hip√≤tesi nul.la.

Gr√†ficament:

L‚Äô√†rea en verd ens mostra a l‚Äôeix de les x la regi√≥ de no rebuig de la \(H_0\), entre el 0.23 i +Inf, mentres que l‚Äô√†rea en vermell ens mostra l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig de \(H_0\), entre 0 i 0.23 Com que el nostre estad√≠stic (4.33) queda dintre de la regi√≥ d‚Äôacceptaci√≥, (l√≠nia negra) no rebutgem \(H_0\).

Exercici 62

A consumer association wants to compare several alkaline battery brands. Two random samples , both of size 50, corresponding to the two main brands in the market (sample A and sample B) are obtained. Each element in each sample is plugged into an electronic device to measure its lifespan. Assume that the lifespan of batteries follows a Normal distribution and that the samples were drawn independently. The sample mean for the lifespan of the batteries in samples A and B were 41 and 45 hours respectively, and the standard deviations 2 and 1.8 hours respectively. Answer the following questions:

  1. Can we infer from the information gathered that the batteries of brand B have a lifespan with less variability? (use a significance level of Œ± = 0.05)

\(H_0: \ \sigma^2_A \le \sigma^2_B\)
\(H_1: \ \sigma^2_A > \sigma^2_B\)

Hem de veure si acceptem o rebutgem \(H_0\), per a fer-ho utilitzem el estad√≠stic \(S^2_A / S^2_B\) (vari√†ncia mostral de la bateria A dividit entre la vari√†ncia mostral de la bateria B). L‚Äôestad√≠stic de la prova (observed value of test statistic, OVTS) √©s \(S_A^2 / S_B^2\).

sa <- 2
sb <- 1.8
(OVTS <- sa^2 / sb^2)  # 1.234568
## [1] 1.234568

Ara busquem l‚Äôestad√≠stic de contrast, el qual es basa en la distribuci√≥ \(F_{na -1, nb -1}\). Al tractar-se d‚Äôun test unilateral dreta (\(H_1: \sigma^2_A > \sigma^2_B\)) i que la significaci√≥ √©s \(\alpha = 0.05\), l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig ser√†:

\([F_{na -1, nb -1, 1-alpha}, +\infty]\)

Utilitzarem la funci√≥ qf() (recomanable veure el help per a exemples d‚Äô√∫s), amb una significaci√≥ \(\alpha = 0.05\)

na <- 50
nb <- 50
alpha <- 0.05
(qf( p = 1-alpha, df1 = na-1, df2 = nb-1 ))  # 1.607289
## [1] 1.607289

Com que 1.23 no entra dintre de la regi√≥ de rebuig [1.61, +Inf), no rebutgem \(H_0\). √âs a dir, no podem dir que la vida √∫til de les bateries de la marca B tingui una variabilitat menor que les de la marca A.

Gr√†ficament:

L‚Äô√†rea en verd √©s de 1-alpha = 0.95 i ens mostra a l‚Äôeix de les x la regi√≥ de no rebuig de la \(H_0\), entre el 0 i 1.61, mentres que l‚Äô√†rea en vermell √©s de alpha = 0.05 i ens mostra l‚Äô√†rea de rebuig de \(H_0\), entre 1.61 i +Inf. Com que el nostre estad√≠stic (1.21) queda dintre de la regi√≥ d‚Äôacceptaci√≥, (l√≠nia negra) no rebutgem \(H_0\)

Quin √©s el p-valor? Haurem de calcular l‚Äô√†rea m√©s a la dreta de la l√≠nia negra [OVTS, +Inf)

pf( OVTS, df1=na-1, df2=nb-1, lower.tail = F ) #  0.2317496
## [1] 0.2317496

En termes de p-valor, no rebutgem \(H_0\) ja que 0.23 > 0.05.
